Infrastructure Device Pattern
  • Infrastructure Device Elements are used to represent physical devices such as physical servers, telecom equipment, and other devices.
  • Please note, Storage, Appliances and Network devices have their own elements to use.
  • This Element's Stereotype extends the UML Device element.
Element Information
  1. Stereotype = Infrastructure Device
  2. Tag Type = Describes main purpose of the Device. For example, "server" type would be used for an IBM Power server.
  3. Tag Summary = A Structured Tag that describes the Appliance's Vendor and Version. If version is unknown, leave it blank or put a period.
Constraints
  • This element is NOT used for Network Devices, Storage Devices, or VM's.
Examples
  • IBM Power Server
  • Avaya Telecom Physical Equipment

Storage Device - NAS Pattern
  • The Storage Device Element is used to represent Network Attached Storage hardware.
  • This element's Structure Component Diagram contains 1 or more Network Share Elements that represent NAS Shares hosted by the device.
Storage Device Element Information
  1. Stereotype = storage device
  2. Tag Type = Describes physical disk type. For example, disk array is used for standard disk spindles. Solid State is used for Flash storage.
  3. Tag Summary = A Structured Tag that describes the Storage's Vendor and Version. If version is unknown, leave it blank.
Network Share Element Information
  1. Stereotype = network_shr
  2. Tag dfs = Defines the DFS path. This field is required for all File Shares (Windows) but left blank for Mount Points (Linux).
  3. Tag mirror = Defines if network share will be mirrored. Default is "No".
  4. Tag path = Defines physical path to network share.
  5. Tag size = Defines File Share size in GBs.
  6. Tag type = Defines Share Type as either "file share" (Windows) or "mount point" (Linux).
Constraints
  • Network Share elements must be tied to at least one NAS Storage device.
Examples
  • tbd
